<Layout title="Control Ch.9 — Kalman Filter" favicon="🎛">
  <main>

    <a href="/reading/control/" class="text-sm mb-4 inline-block">&larr; back to Control Theory</a>

    <h1>Kalman Filter</h1>
    <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-6">Wikipedia &middot; <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalman_filter"><img src="/reading/wikipedia.svg" alt="wp" style="display:inline;height:1em;vertical-align:-0.1em;margin-right:0.2em;"/>Kalman filter</a> &middot; CC BY-SA 4.0</p>

    <div class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-5 mb-8 callout">
      <p class="text-lg" style="max-width:none">The <strong>Kalman filter</strong> estimates the state of a linear system from noisy measurements. Each step has two phases: <strong>predict</strong> (use the model to forecast the next state) and <strong>update</strong> (correct the forecast using the measurement). It is optimal in the least-squares sense for Gaussian noise.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>Prediction and update</h3>
    <p><strong>Predict</strong>: propagate the state estimate forward using the system model. The uncertainty grows. <strong>Update</strong>: incorporate the new measurement. The Kalman gain weights how much to trust the measurement versus the prediction. If the measurement is precise (low noise), the gain is high and you trust the sensor. If the model is precise (low process noise), the gain is low and you trust the prediction.</p>

    <!-- SVG: Noisy measurements converging to true state -->
